@startuml fig-osi-l5-l6
skinparam backgroundColor white
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 12
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam roundcorner 12

title OSI reference model — focus on L5 and L6

rectangle "L7  Application\n(HTTP, DNS, SMTP, FTP)" as l7 #BBDEFB
rectangle "L6  Presentation\n(data formats, encoding, compression)" as l6 #E1BEE7
rectangle "L5  Session\n(dialogue control, state, resumption)" as l5 #FFE0B2
rectangle "L4  Transport\n(TCP, UDP, TLS)" as l4 #F5F5F5
rectangle "L3  Network\n(IP, ICMP, routing)" as l3 #F5F5F5
rectangle "L2  Data Link\n(Ethernet, Wi-Fi, MAC)" as l2 #ECEFF1
rectangle "L1  Physical\n(bits, signals, cables)" as l1 #ECEFF1

l7 -[hidden]down- l6
l6 -[hidden]down- l5
l5 -[hidden]down- l4
l4 -[hidden]down- l3
l3 -[hidden]down- l2
l2 -[hidden]down- l1

note right of l6
  Modern Internet:
  L6 functions live inside
  libraries and application
  protocols (JSON, UTF-8, gzip).
end note

note right of l5
  Modern Internet:
  L5 functions are handled by
  cookies, tokens, TLS session
  resumption and WebSockets.
end note

legend bottom
  L5 (Session) and L6 (Presentation) are conceptual layers.
  On today's Internet they are not separate wire-level protocols.
  Their responsibilities are absorbed by L7 applications and middleware.
endlegend
@enduml
